24 itaque eius modi libri extant etc. : The evident meaning of this disputed passage is this: Such is the inspiring influence of great trials, such the stimulating effect of intensely interested audiences, that even speakers of mediocre ability will in spite of themselves be impelled to higher efforts, and hence posterity bases its opinion of the accused and its estimation of the accusers almost exclusively upon the speeches delivered on these occasions, how- ever acceptable in themselves other orator-ical productions of the same speakers may have been.

The passage seems, therefore, perfectly sound‚ being virtually little more than a striking, concrete illustration of the truth of the general statements immediately preceding: ‘ splendor reorum . . . et ipsa plurimum eloquentiae praestant . . . crescit cum amplitudine rerum vis ingenii (c. 37 15. 21). Andresen's emendation, though ingenious, is consequently not called for, not to mention that ‘legerunt’ in place of ‘legunt' is sufficient to invali-
